				<h3 id=post-380> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/why-i-sponsor-frontlinesmscredit/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到我为什么要赞助FrontlineSMS：信用">为什么我赞助FrontlineSMS：信用</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于2009年12月22日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/why-i-sponsor-frontlinesmscredit/#comments" title="评论为什么我赞助FrontlineSMS：信用">1条评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  > 2008年7月，我正坐在易趣领导培训，并要求告诉小组什么启发对我的工作我。</span> <span  >我站起来，并立即开始告诉的马赛部落前，我曾访问过度假时，一个星期的故事。</span> <span  >这些人没有自来水，没有电...他们的传统服饰，美丽的红色和紫色毛毯穿着。</span> <span  >这些飞机支。</span> <span  >他们的鞋是由旧的轮胎。</span> <span  >他们很少或几乎没有现代奢侈品，但他们确实有一台设备...移动电话。</span> </p><p> <span  >当时，我曾驾驶PayPal移动的业务在北美地区近两年来的发展努力和实现，没有理由为什么这些马赛应该无法参与全球经济的任何更长的时间，eBay网站上出售或接受他们的产品从国外汇款使用移动电话。</span> <span  >唯一的限制因素是我们的想象，我们的希望，我们的能力来连接这些点，我们知道如何做到这一点。</span> <span  >就在那一刻，我描绘了理想，我会做到这一点，我将有助于建立的移动支付系统，摆脱那些谁也给那些谁需要钱，让这些人有更长期的财政稳定和连接全球市场。</span> <span  >我会用我曾在过去三年在移动支付和手机银行几年中所获得这样做的知识。</span> <span  >离开贝宝不久，我开始我的咨询实践移动支付<a href="http://www.mpayconnect.com/"target=_blank>，www.mpayconnect.com</a>并一直与客户合作，以实现这一愿景。</span> </p><p> <span  >在此期间，一个朋友告诉我，肯银行推出了给我们发电子邮件。</span> <span  >经过近6个月的网络空间，肯和我沟通，在旧金山开会的人。</span> <span  >当我了解到FrontlineSMS多，我想起了在2000-2003年的开源回去工作，并知道它的破坏力与服务器可用于移动支付使用了。</span> <span  >我问他我怎么能帮助他的基础上推出网上支付平台之上垂直。</span> <span  >他疑惑地看着我说：“你不知道本？”</span> </p><p> <span  >当我听到本里昂和他犯下的近20人的志愿者队伍与前线做短信：信用，我不得不帮助他们把他们的努力推向市场。</span> <span  >本和我在纽约会见了耶鲁俱乐部之一，另一个非洲同事下午。</span> <span  >正如我们在该俱乐部的讨论非洲非正规金融系统坐着，移动支付的权力，和互操作性的需要，我决定捐赠他的努力。</span> </p><p><span  >我们需要像FrontlineSMS和FrontlineSMS组织：信贷，以实现财政列入世界的看法范围。</span> <span  >而不是理由的理由的所有移动支付和互操作性是难以或不可能发生，本和他的团队一直在推动其前进。</span> <span  >他们努力想照顾的人谁最需要的，在一天结束时，是最重要的组成部分考虑各种需要。</span> <span  >我的希望是，我们小的捐赠，将帮助实现这些转移到谁的谁在那些有需要的是金钱远见，让这些人有更长期的财政稳定。</span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/mPay.png alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>梅内克谢Gencer姆佩是连接，并为寻求推出移动支付咨询服务的主要客户。</em></span> <span  > <em>连接姆佩专门提供战略，业务发展和产品规划的援助。</em></span> <span  > <em>在成立之前姆佩连接，梅内克谢领导的PayPal移动商务发展的努力。</em></span> <span  > <em>在此期间，她获得PayPal的第一个移动网络运营商处理</em> ， <em>并展开贝宝发送Sprint的移动钱包钱。</em></span> <span  > <em>在此之前，她跑企业软件网关的产品规划部。</em></span> <span  > <em>连接姆佩FrontlineSMS是第一个正式赞助商：信用。</em></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-378> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/india-i-feel-you/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到印度，我觉得你。">印度，我觉得你。</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a> 12月<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> 12日，由主机2009 - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/india-i-feel-you/#respond" title="印度评论，我觉得你。">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >在<a href="http://conferences.ted.com/TEDIndia/program/">印度的TED会议</a>是一个伟大的起跳点开始，我需要寻找在印度的研究。</span> <span  >我继续为各地的研究机会月份全国旅游会议结束后，参加会议的人们和在班加罗尔，迈索尔，Ahmedebad，村庄乌代和拉贾斯坦，德里，孟买和卢迪亚纳组织。</span> <span  >我是只打算让我做有助于，从整体上-当然通过我的机构，无论其产品在个人层面上，以及。</span> <span  >在我所有的时间在火车，飞机，汽车和autorickshaws这里的主题和我的旅行宰杀道理：</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>设计贫穷：</strong>印度光开关，楼梯和地板不规则的高度，在视频通信混乱，假冒伪劣的接纳为规范工业设计，完全没有进入设计，任何公共或私人空间，一般在80杂音％的情况太糟糕的用户体验它会给你一个头痛的问题。</span> <span  >更何况噪音污染的每一个角落encouragment印度。</span> <span  >我知道没有一个外人，或内幕真的可以改变印度-事实上，印度文化是不会改变的-我希望它不会。</span> <span  >但是小的变化，提高与印度的设计师正确的教育和教育程度越来越高，从消费者的权利要求的质量和生活经验，可以作出很大的不同，以印度的整体。</span> <span  >摆脱贫困的方法可以设计成这样进行教育。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>反向散居：</strong>许多像我这样的印度人，是在国外长大正在返回印度加入“野生，野生东方”。</span> <span  >特德它觉得好像1人/ 3是来自硅谷和尽管印度与硅谷对流以及技术人才的成立，我很高兴地看到我们这一代是如何使用的社会效益和它设计美好的世界。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>矛盾的空间：</strong>印度是一个巨大的矛盾，印度人的工作和生活在这个矛盾的空间，每天和舒适，在这个空间的平衡。</span> <span  >这将有助于解释有关，有时会发生冲突时，外国公司来印度预期的平稳过渡<a href="http://devdutt.com/">。Devdutt Pattanaik</a>在谈话中介绍这一解释与东方和西方，他们踢得如何在商业和文化差异的根本原因位。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>Jugaad：</strong>找到一个解决方法。</span> <span  > Jugaad的字面意思是安排或解决，而这些均因缺乏资源使用。</span> <span  >印度人亦一直Jugaad，这在本质上是做得不正规的方式，而是操纵一个人的方式，找到绕过回答&#39;漏洞没有&#39;。</span> <span  >印度人不喜欢听或说没有。</span> <span  >有几乎总是从某种意义上说，这是一个伟大的居住心态</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>土著发明：</strong>财政和物质是由最终用户发明的产品更有价值的东西比一个人的，我们设计了他们。</span> <span  >在<a href="http://www.sristi.org/hbnew/">蜜蜂网络</a>和他们的发明和<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chit_fund">节基金</a>是这个伟大的例子。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>破坏性一切：</strong>破坏性的商业模式，破坏性的设计，思考，讨论-这一切，正在接受越来越多的印度和世界的一个更具吸引力的选择比久经考验。</span> <span  >中断不仅源于创新，但更重要的是使公平竞争的民主。</span> <span  >我绝对同意这个主题。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>Philanthrocapitalism：</strong>或者，同情心的业务，我喜欢称呼它，往往是烤成许多印度公司。</span> <span  >文化上，社会责任，是人们日常生活的一部分，因此其大部分在印度事后比其他地方少。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>腐败：</strong>没有一件事已经停止印度的进步不止这些。</span> <span  >之前也做更透明的方式，以及受贿消失，它将会是非常困难的印度将成为世界领袖，应该是。</span> <span  >我希望自己的反腐败斗争的运气<a href="http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/life/2005/08/19/stories/2005081900080200.htm">Shaffi马瑟</a>手。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>孩子们：</strong>据悉，在印度真正的改变，世界将与下一代，在印度的教育需要一场革命，现在。</span> <span  >许多人都这样做，包括基兰塞西的<a href="http://www.schoolriverside.com/">滨江学校</a>和新浪娱乐多希谁带来<a href="0">香格里拉新学校</a>到印度。</span> <span  >随着教育的责任，烤到他们的权利类型，为可持续发展或社会变革或设计思想，它的下一代就是改变生活。</span> <span  >尽管如此，拥有世界上最大，最年轻的经济，可能会变成它的最大实惠是印度最大的批评之一。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>手机真理：</strong>大家都知道它的重要银行的开设银行账户，建立支付系统。</span> <span  >我看到，在许多地方还没有被用来尚未充分发挥其潜力，如在教育部门，在食品，在广告和公共服务-这可能真的被证明是最好的工具，以解决在印度大规模的问题。</span> </p><p> <span  >多来我的过程和消化这方面的研究难以置信的一个月。</span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_raina.jpg alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>这个职位是由雷伊内库姆拉贡献，交通银行主任FrontlineSMS：信用。</em></span> </p><p> <span  > <em>要联系雷伊内，电子邮件</em></span> <em><br /></em> <span  > <a href=mailto:raina@credit.frontlinesms.com><em>raina@credit.frontlinesms.com。</em></a></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-376> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/the-hidden-side-of-cash/" rel=bookmark title="永久连结现金隐藏的一面">在现金隐藏的一面</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于2009年12月7日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">职位</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/the-hidden-side-of-cash/#respond" title="评论现金隐藏的一面">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >想象一下，明天醒来发现每你拥有流动性资产已由1美元的法案取代的价值。</span> <span  >这与500美元限额的信用卡？</span> <span  >它只是爆裂500 $ 1秒你的钱包的接缝。</span> <span  >您的$ 30,000退休帐户？</span> <span  >祝你好运，即使发现根据该现金山区桌面。</span> <span  >但在此之前落户的研究计算出来，你可能要锁定后门，因为我不会把它过去的邻居，以帮助自己的钱数一把。</span> <span  > （毕竟，盗窃现金是很容易，打击别人的网上银行帐户。）财务管理公司在这个世界上新的和惊人文字的扭曲。</span> </p><p> <span  >事实上，如果你碰巧住在金沙萨，刚果，出现上述情况的民主共和国首都将是一个drearily熟悉的场景，而不是一个有趣的思想实验。</span> <span  >最正式的金融服务，如储蓄，支票，信用卡，几乎不存在在刚果民主共和国，并在当地货币最大的法案是500法郎的钞票-价值约在编写时0.55。</span> <span  >对于典型的刚果商人-说，一名女子卖150法郎（约合0.17美元）的杯子在Makala木薯面粉市场-一个很好的一天的销售额将意味着相当不方便的法郎桩携带。</span> <span  >另一种方法是付出代价转化为美国的美元，刚果民主共和国的非官方的第二大货币，它具有较高的教派和较低的通货膨胀率来的法郎-并留下一一点，结果较差。</span> </p><p> <span  >尽管与小土堆处理法案明显的麻烦，但是，它甚至可以说是最严重的问题，刚果民主共和国的现金只有经济提出的问题。</span> <span  >当我在采访小额信贷客户在金沙萨今年早些时候，我印象最深的是一些人说，他们谁的现金被盗-无论是在街上，在他们的家园，甚至未来的小额信贷银行凭借其新出获得贷款资金捆绑到他们的pagnes角落整齐，和等待，以满足他们的聪明的小偷。</span> <span  >这是现金隐藏的一面，留下一个本已脆弱的穷人更容易受到盗窃，少能够进行私下的任何类型的金融交易。</span> <span  >这就是为什么，如果小额金融业真正致力于为穷人服务，它需要的现金后离开，拥抱移动银行。</span> </p><p><span  >在刚果民主共和国的国家一样，移动小额信贷很可能提供的第一和唯一的机会，大多数人要进行金融交易，方便，私人和安全的-在已为几十年来在西方理所当然的交易类型。</span> <span  >这个从现金转换的影响，移动真的不为过。</span> <span  >毕竟，如果你愿意是-从方便管理您的笔记本电脑或移动电话，或站立超过1美元的法案后卫组成您一生的积蓄，现在在你（新磊）床垫填充您的银行帐户？</span> </p><p> <span  >我是这么想的。</span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_rachel.jpg alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>这个职位是雷切尔斯特罗姆作出了贡献，撒哈拉以南非洲地区协调员FrontlineSMS：信用。</em></span> </p><p> <span  > <em>要联系雷切尔，电子邮件</em></span> <em><br /></em> <span  > <a href=mailto:rachel@credit.frontlinesms.com><em>rachel@credit.frontlinesms.com。</em></a></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-358> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/microloans-in-rural-areas-through-mobile-phones/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到农村七千五百万通过手机">在农村地区通过手机七千五百万</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于09年12月3日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/12/microloans-in-rural-areas-through-mobile-phones/#comments" title="评论在农村地区通过手机七千五百万">1条评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >不久，拉丁美洲和加勒比地区（LAC）的农村居民将获得意外的对小额贷款，储蓄和保险... ...，并通过他们的移动电话。</span> <span  >这表明在（MFI）的小额信贷机构的趋势，越来越先进的移动支付系统及开放源码程序，作为两者之间的桥梁的出现。</span> </p><p> <span  >这个职位将简要地解释小额信贷机构和工作的移动支付，开放源码软件如何能够促进经济融合和什么样的挑战面对这一进程。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>导言</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/jorge_post_1.jpg alt="" /> <span  >据世界银行，只有35％的拉丁美洲和加勒比的人口获得金融服务。</span> <span  >这这样的情况，减少了支付，储蓄和信贷的选择和限制他们的融资渠道的低效率和更加昂贵。</span> </p><p> <span  >获得储蓄，信贷，保险和其他金融服务是必要的，以改善你的立场和克服不可预见的紧急金融情况（医疗费，教育收费，偶尔失业...）。</span> <span  >此外，适当的财务规划，使家庭和企业家，以提高其业务成长的机会，减少收入的波动（即消费平滑），凝聚人的储蓄和财产，并最终提高他们的能力，应对经济冲击。</span> </p><p> <span  >最近的研究表明，库存的个人和家庭经济条件较佳谁比那些缺乏获得正规的金融服务。</span> <span  >在某种程度上，收入和储蓄增加，库存的个人抵御金融危机，可以从简单的日常生存到中期和长期规划。</span> </p><p> <span  >这些情况是特别重要的是在农村地区，欠发达地区和城市，一般来说在非正规部门，只能由手机访问控制这些地方。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>小额信贷机构</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignright src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/jorge_post_2.jpg alt="" /> <span  >小额信贷和融资来上升20世纪70年代，当社会企业家开始提供小额贷款和其他金融服务，谁没有来由于缺乏担保的正式访问的财政穷人企业家。</span> </p><p> <span  >拉丁美洲和加勒比一些贫穷国家的小额信贷发展的先锋。</span> <span  >这方面一直没有停止发展，已经达到这样的程度<a href="http://idbdocs.iadb.org/wsdocs/getdocument.aspx?docnum=2189221">，2009年全球显微镜</a>研究是由著名的财经刊物经济学家上市秘鲁，玻利维亚，准备，厄瓜多尔和哥伦比亚（顺序）的前十位国家与世界更好的营商小额信贷环境。</span> </p><p><span  >大多数小额信贷机构开始作为非政府非营利组织（非政府组织），农村银行或其他金融合作社，或国家开发银行。</span> <span  >随着时间的推移，对小额信贷机构的许多人成为非营利性机构，因为这是一个许可证和提供储蓄服务的需求。</span> <span  >以营利为目的小额信贷机构可以归到非银行金融机构，商业银行或专门从事小额信贷的银行，提供各类服务财政部门。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>移动支付</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >移动支付是一个系统，允许用户存入移动钱包的钱和分配通过短信（SMS）它。</span> <span  >移动支付更快，更便宜比将钱存入银行，邮局或长途巴士司机。</span> <span  >通过使用这种付款类型，农村人可以放弃前往银行或邮局，以获取资金和转让，因此，可以投入更多的时间来生产活动。</span> </p><p> <span  >移动支付也是一个途径是实行财政剥夺权力社区正规的金融服务。</span> </p><p> <span  >移动支付的先锋，如小额贷款，是在贫穷国家的企业家，谁认识到，他们可以透过出售服务的经济金字塔（国际收支）基础货币。</span> <span  >有两个原因：这个市场的规模和人口之间的流动电话渗透率率高的原因。</span> </p><p> <span  > <a href="http://www.safaricom.co.ke/index.php?id=745">Safaricom公司的M - PESA（</a>肯尼亚）， <a href="http://smart.com.ph/">智能货币</a> （菲律宾）， <a href="http://web.globe.com.ph/">环球集团现金</a> （菲律宾）是其中的先驱者。</span> <span  >智能理财＆G公司现金单独带来大约二万七千五点零零万每月菲律宾美元！</span> <span  >若要了解更多关于如何典型的移动支付系统的运作方式，请参阅<a href="http://www.splash-cash.com/pdf/using-splash.pdf">现金飞溅</a> （塞拉利昂）， <a href="http://www.obopay.co.in/mobile_obopay.html">将Obopay（</a>印度）和<a href="http://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=p/gen/mobile-outside">贝宝</a> （美国）的信息。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>如何开放源码软件促进金融包容性</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/jorge_post_3.jpg alt="" /> <span  >看看下面的例子：一个需要钱的农民在市场租一个摊位出售其产品。</span> <span  >目前，他也没有其他办法得到它。</span> <span  >最有可能的，他便要到最近的MFI和申请微型（与信用贷款利率可以达到28％左右，根据<a href="http://www.cgap.org/">咨询小组</a> ， <a href="http://www.cgap.org/">协助穷人</a> ）。</span> <span  >他需要长途跋涉的小额信贷机构支付每周偿还贷款。</span> </p><p> <span  >随着移动支付系统，在我们的例子农民应该能够避免费时（过境时间）和金钱（运输成本获得贷款），通过他的手机的机会成本。</span> <span  >从理论上说，这种交易应该很简单。</span> </p><p> <span  >但在实践中，小额信贷机构提供有困难的，甚至在非洲和亚洲国家有移动支付渠道等服务。</span> <span  >为什么？</span> <span  >小额信贷机构缺乏一种软件无缝集成与管理信息系统，移动支付。</span> </p><p> <span  >与处理支付能力将有助于解决上述问题，发展自由和开放源码软件。</span> <span  >这个软件将提供一个在移动支付系统和小额信贷机构的桥梁，使小额信贷机构使用移动支付的款项分发给群众，自动生成客户信用记录，维持充裕的审计路径。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>挑战</strong></span> </p><p> <span  > Frontlinesms：信用是一项倡议，旨在为通过简单的文字信息（SMS）的正规的金融服务，农村和断开人口。</span> <span  >合并自由开放的<a href="http://www.frontlinesms.com/">Frontlinesms，</a>而成为一个大众短信通讯枢纽一台电脑，有能力处理突出的移动支付系统和小额贷款结合起来，共同管理制度，FrontlineSMS：信用卡将有利于拉丁美洲和加勒比地区金融包容源码软件。</span> </p><p> <span  >该任务FrontlineSMS：信贷面临的是不容易的。</span> <span  >一方面是监管环境，使作为金融包容的工具使用移动电话。</span> <span  >虽然一些国家以及先进的领域，特别是秘鲁和墨西哥（见<a href="http://movilybanca.afi.es/2009/09/09/america-latina-en-contexto-entorno-para-los-servicios-financieros-moviles/">拉丁美洲中文contexto：埃尔entorno第斯财务服务Móviles公司</a> ），在拉丁美洲和加勒比各国政府还远远没有创造有利环境了。</span> </p><p> <span  >另一方面是移动支付系统在该地区的发展。</span> <span  >幸运的是，几个系统已经出现了：在巴拉圭， <a href="http://www.arturogoga.com/2009/05/20/se-lanza-en-per-el-modelo-de-pagos-por-celular/">果Móvil公司</a> <a href="http://www.tigocash.com.py/">Tigo现金</a> ，在墨西哥和<a href="http://www.novaoi.com.br/">爱Paggo</a>在秘鲁， <a href="http://nipper.com.mx/">钳</a>在巴西有几个。</span> </p><p> <span  >不要忘记还有分销网络，移动支付系统，市场营销，交易安全互操作性，客户的信任，移动电话平台，透明度等辅助功能。</span> </p><p> <span  > FrontlineSMS：信用一直致力于生产10月以来的开放源码工具的范围扩大移动支付功能。</span> <span  >它的模块之一将准备进行实地试验和春季免费下载无论是在非洲或亚洲，在那里我们看到，移动支付系统，非常发达。</span> <span  >在拉丁美洲和加勒比我们在2011年年初，或更早，如果情况许可。</span> </p><p> <span  >短暂的发展史是与虚假的承诺，并没有充满基准，本里昂说，执行FrontlineSMS主任：信用，既不移动支付，也不应崇高的小额信贷作为下一个&#39;银弹。</span> <span  >然而，移动支付系统的整个发展中世界的迅速崛起提出了一个数十亿人民的巨大和令人激动的机会...我们必须抓住这个机会！</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>[ <a href="http://textosms.wordpress.com/2009/12/03/microprestamos-en-zonas-rurales-a-traves-de-telefonos-moviles/"target=_blank>阅读本文西班牙在豪尔赫的博客文章</a> ]</strong></span> </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_jorge.jpg alt="" /><br /> <span  > <em>这个职位是由Jorge湖贡献阿隆索湾，南美洲区域协调员FrontlineSMS：信用。</em></span> </p><p> <span  > <em>要联系豪尔赫，电子邮件</em></span> <em><br /></em> <span  > <a href=mailto:jorge@credit.frontlinesms.com><em>jorge@credit.frontlinesms.com。</em></a></span> </p><h5> <span  > ____________________</span> <br /> <span  > <em>征询的消息来源：</em></span> <br /> <span  > 1。 <a href="http://www.fundacionandares.org/">基金会第斯发展委员会拉斯Microfinanzas，Andares</a></span> <br /> <span  > <a href="http://microrate.com/es/home/about-microfinance/general-information-on-microfinance">2。MicroRate：为小额信贷评级机构</a></span> <br /> <span  > <a href="http://movilybanca.afi.es/">3。Telefonía Móvil公司辎Acceso一财务服务ý中文拉丁美洲和加勒比</a></span> </h5></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-346> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/ict4d-mission-drift-waste/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接ICT4D，团漂移和废弃物">ICT4D，使命漂移和废弃物</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a> 11月<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">员额</a> 30日由本里昂2009年- <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/ict4d-mission-drift-waste/#respond" title="评论ICT4D，使命漂移和废弃物">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >信息通信技术促进发展，或ICT4D，是在发展空间越来越热门的话题。</span> <span  >是好还是坏，甚至可能成为下一个热潮-要一个独特的挑战，世界默认的响应情况。</span> <span  >如果60年的发展历史表明什么，那就是使命漂移和废弃物，宣传可能副产品，其结果既不受益人也不ICT4D医生可以负担的。</span> <span  >为了避免这样的结果，是ICT4D社会必须接受谦虚，谨慎，耐心其日益增长的知名度，和自我监督。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>谦卑</strong></span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/ict4d_post_01.jpg class=alignright> <span  >最根本的，我们必须承认，技术是不是解决办法，而是一个工具，该工具包。</span> <span  >无论从技术解决方案的结果基本上是对用户的吸收和智慧的结果。</span> <span  >最终用户杠杆移动计算技术，例如，创建通话转让和&#39;闪光&#39;，就像Twitter的用户，不仅@答复和哈希标签出来的，而是从改变“你在干什么？”到“共享其根本目的并发现发生的事情现在在世界任何地方“。</span> <span  >超过1 / 3在肯尼亚的M - PESA客户掌握在自己的移动钱包非正式储蓄和使用Twitter的伊朗人，迫使主流媒体报道（记得＃CNNfail？）的进一步证明。</span> <span  >技术供应商的促进，而不是白色骑士。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>注意</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >正如一般，这不是游戏的发展。</span> <span  >真实的生活和生计的路线和错误，有严重的后果。</span> <span  >因此，必须技术方便，廉价，耐用和直观。</span> <span  >没有远见和承诺的长期可持续性，供应商可能会创建用户只撷取基地从下他们发言时，才商业模式失败。</span> <span  >举例来说，你可以想象，数以百万计的菲律宾人将受到影响，如果不是金钱或GCASH智能去下。</span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/ict4d_post_02.jpg class=alignleft> <span  > <strong>耐心</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >在半世界指挥家和光纤，很难想象进展非指数计算。</span> <span  >在发展中世界，但是，墨菲和马斯洛有关得多比穆尔。</span> <span  >尽管令人难以置信的增长暴-跨越-在电信和互联网普及率，有大量工作仍然没有完成的逐步增长。</span> <span  >因此，一些技术比其他人更合适，因为它们应对当前的市场失灵和用户的需求。</span> <span  >云计算和机器人，例如，将极大地改变未来的发展景观，但大部分仍停留在目前的不恰当的。</span> <span  > ICT4D从业人员因此，应推动&#39;，而不是试图以&#39;推动&#39;的&#39;下一件大事&#39;拉&#39;。</span> <span  >更简单地，供应由需求驱动，而不是相反。</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>自省</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >每个人都谈到自豪和的倾向，特别是在发展中的表。</span> <span  >对信息和通信技术行业最大的资产之一是其在工程，由简单的问题，推动科学重点：如何使过程X更有效率？</span> <span  >一旦我们加上“四维”的公式，但是，我们推出一系列冲突的意识形态和做法主机转移从量变到质变的焦点。</span> <span  >至于ICT4D继续增长，我们必须不断地问自己：什么偏见和眼罩，我们提请表？</span> </p><p> <span  > <strong>最后...</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >我们不能让ICT4D成为其自身成功的受害者。</span> <span  >为了帮助减轻各种挑战和本地区的运作情况下，关键是我们要不断地重新以下四个问题：</span> </p><ol><li> <span  >我们如何促进有机解决当地问题？</span> </li><li> <span  >如何将用户受到影响，如果我们不能？</span> </li><li> <span  >我们立足于推动或拉动我们的策略？</span> </li><li> <span  >我们的效率或自我驱动？</span> </li></ol><p></p><hr /><span  > <strong>阿育王：</strong> <em>创新的公共承载在海得拉巴，印度，在2010年2月技术协会4，会议探讨的技术，发明和社会变革。</em></span> <span  > <em>了解有关这次会议的更多信息<a href="http://tech.ashoka.org/"target=_blank>：http://tech.ashoka.org。</a></em></span> <span  > <em>这个博客帖子是在其竞争进入官方博客找到旅行和采访。</em></span> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-337> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/microsave-3rd-generation-microfinance/" rel=bookmark title="永久链接到微额和第三代小额信贷">微额与第三代小额信贷</a></span> </h3> <span  > <small>张贴在<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">博客</a>于2009年11月21日由东道国<a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="查看所有帖子在博客帖子" rel="category tag">职位</a> - <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/microsave-3rd-generation-microfinance/#respond" title="在微额和第三代评论小额信贷">成为第一位评论</a></small></span> <div class=entry><p> <span  >在非洲开始于1998年，微<a href="http://www.microsave.org/">（www.MicroSave.org）</a>现在是一个近80经验丰富的专业团队已经运作了十多年的，并且经常受到客户的描述为“金融服务供应商最可信赖的咨询公司”。</span> <span  >在内罗毕，坎帕拉，勒克瑙，海得拉巴，微工程办公室在亚洲和非洲将一份关于在商业中心的客户强烈关注，并制造产品和运载系统的客户端响应或“市场主导”。</span> </p><p> <span  >微额特别是众所周知的实地层次的研究，这需要与穷人广泛的访问（包括小额信贷客户），以便更好地了解他们的财务行为和风险状况。</span> <span  >微额的行动研究小额信贷机构，以更好地协助听取客户和设计更好的市场信息为基础适当的金融产品。</span> <span  >这两个研究活动是相辅相成的，直接反馈到工具箱/课程开发和传播工作。</span> </p><p> <span  >其核心研究和紧密合作，共同的经验与亚洲多种多样的合作伙伴和非洲使微额开发和测试一系列的实践基础和实践为重点，培训课程和工作坊-它的“工具包”。</span> <span  >微额采用了结构化方法在其国际知名的工具包为基础的服务提供给客户。</span> <span  >这些工具包得到了广泛的好评，并已成为20多个不同语言的翻译。</span> <span  >微额工具箱现在用于全球各地。</span> <span  >该工具包为基础的方针，确保一步一步外地任务，这将产生空前的一致性和质量的过程。</span> </p><p> <span  >欲了解更多见<a href="http://www.microsave.org/static/content/microsave-history">微额历史</a></span> </p><p> <span  >几年来，微一直密切参与了多个电子和在非洲和亚洲米银行倡议的“软方e”的特别工作，/米银行在技术与客户的接口。</span> <span  >因此，微额进行了密切合作，其中包括沃达丰公司的M - PESA，肯尼亚邮政储蓄银行的现金Xpress和江湖- Airtel公司，印度国家银行，Drishtee - HDFC银行，mChek和许多其他方面提供支持/市场研究机构进行各种过程映射和分析，试验，测试，客户界面和满意度，渠道开发，品牌/营销和财务此外教育等，微每年举行的“M -银行对话”，汇集了供应商的实际执行选择小组米银行的解决方案。</span> <span  >这些对话让医生讨论一些事情的本质与发展中国家的细节和涉及的挑战，测试和推出了英/米银行的解决方案。</span> <span  >这些对话已经证明了巨大的参与者，谁通过同行对等交流的重要学习留下宝贵的。</span> <span  >欲了解更多有关我们与结果或米经验的银行，见<a href="http://www.microsave.org/mobile_banking">http://www.microsave.org/mobile_banking。</a></span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/microsave_post_03.jpg></p><p><span  > <strong>描述生态系统在印度的小额贷款？</strong></span> <span  > <strong>做任何挑战脱颖而出？</strong></span> </p><p> <span  >印度的小额信贷的演变在过去两年以来，在90年代初成立以来几十年。</span> <span  >二次谐波银行联动的模式，它的第一个原型，是从与民间社会的社会中介的作用和银行金融中介不可能结婚后代的打点和NABARD，更愿意助产士行事。</span> </p><p> <span  >随着业务的潜在小额恍然大悟，许多人来说，（MFI）的小额信贷机构对两者的社会和金融中介的任务了。</span> <span  >因此，小额信贷的一个备用通道抵达（姗姗来迟的相比，在世界其他地方）。</span> <span  >这是印度第二代小额信贷。</span> <span  >对小额信贷机构大多采用的连带责任组（JLGs）方法，基本上是原来的乡村集体贷款等模式，标准化成为实现快速增长的新口头禅。</span> <span  >在过去的2-3年，NBFC，小额信贷机构主要是英联合联络小组下经营为基础的方法已成为重要的和迅速增长的力量。</span> </p><p> <span  >新兴的小额信贷机构的数目，以及其产品相对狭窄的重点，意味着激烈的竞争局面已经出现，特别是在南部各州和东部的一些有限的地区。</span> <span  >这为我们提供了前所未有的访问小额信贷借款人。</span> <span  >这一直是他们的好事，但并非没有竞争伴随而来的恶习。</span> <span  >较大的小额信贷机构现在许多的响应非常迅速扩展其商业股票投资者的要求，采取“销售”驱动的增加外展方法。</span> <span  >在迅猛发展，也看到一些小额信贷过度扩张的管理能力和制度，在重大问题所导致的投资组合。</span> </p><p> <span  >为了应对激烈的竞争小额信贷的尝试不同的方法，范围从绝望到故意的。</span> <span  >绝望的措施，像接壤不道德偷猎“既信贷官员和微型金融机构甚至竞争对手群体”。</span> <span  >其他更刻意包括提供个人贷款（白细胞介素）他们老客户的产品。</span> <span  >但是，许多微型金融机构&#39;白介素产品设计很少从他们的集体贷款不同-除了该集团的保证是由一个单一的担保人所取代。</span> <span  >企业的基本评价通常是执行，但产品很少定制，以应对现金流，甚至融资需求，并反映了预先定义的加强贷款计划。</span> <span  >很少小额投资技能的成功方案所需的白细胞介素。</span> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/microsave_post_02.jpg class=alignleft> Given the saturation in a growing number of geographic markets, it is imperative for the MFIs to shift from a “product centric” to a “client centric” approach. The product-centric approach worked in uncompetitive markets with a huge demand-supply gap, and when the imperative was for rapid expansion. But as the number and outreach of MFIs has grown, supply is no more a constraint in many regions. Clients are in a position to pick-and-choose the MFI that offers them the most value. 3rd Generation MFIs will be quick to sense this “tectonic shift” in the dynamics of the highly competitive markets, and do everything they can to put the client back at the centre of their business. This focus will translate into a respect for client&#39;s time and dignity, and into making the entire spectrum of financial services for her livelihood available to her – a welcome prospect for both clients and those who believe in microfinance as a service for development and poverty eradication. </p><p>3rd Generation MFIs will operationalise the strategy of deepening engagement by: </p><ol><li> Offering clients a suite of financial services in response to their full spectrum of financial needs – credit, savings, remittances, insurance etc. </li><li> Focusing on convenience for all clients – so that products respond to clients&#39; needs, and not just those of the institution. </li><li> Leverage technology, particularly e-/m-banking to increase transaction efficiency and reduce costs. </li><li> Add supplementary services, such as the “livelihood” services or education/food security services or possibly even health services. </li></ol><p> For more see <a href="http://bit.ly/M7rOW">http://bit.ly/M7rOW</a> and <a href="http://bit.ly/2Sihm">http://bit.ly/2Sihm</a> </p><p> <strong>The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has a reputation for maintaining strict regulations for both microfinance and mobile payments. With those regulations beginning to lessen, what opportunities and challenges do you see on the horizon?</strong> </p><p> The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) brought out the Banking Correspondent circular in January 2006 to enable banks to establish correspondent relationships for delivery of basic financial services to the un-banked and under banked segments of the society in areas without bank branches nearby. Another circular was subsequently issued, restricting correspondents to not-for-profit entities. Despite the obvious limitations imposed by the regulator, perhaps in a bid to test the waters, the banks launched major initiatives for financial inclusion in underserved geographies. Some of the large public sector banks managed good outreach and in a period of less than two years, more than a million clients were &#39;banked&#39;. However, by the own admission of the banks and the technology providers, more than 85% of the accounts opened under the correspondent model are “dormant”. This has brought banks to a stage where the thought is, “Are initiatives under the banking correspondent channel a business proposition or is it a corporate social responsibility initiative?” The evidence so far is that banks have concluded that under the current regulations, it is a CSR activity. Accordingly accounts are opened and reported to the RBI but transactions are not encouraged. </p><p> The Working Group established to review the Banking Correspondent Model under P. Vijaya Bhaskar in its report submitted on 18 August, 2009, made a series of recommendations, many of which were endorsed by Dr. D. Subbarao, Governor, Reserve Bank of India in the Second Quarter Review of Monetary Policy for the Year 2009-10. In the Review, the Governor noted, “Based on the Group&#39;s  recommendations, it is proposed: </p><ul><li> to allow banks to appoint the following entities as BCs in addition to those permitted already: (i) individual kirana [small retail]/medical/fair price shop owners;  (ii) individual public call office (PCO) operators; (iii) agents of small savings schemes of Government of India/insurance companies; (iv) individuals who own petrol pumps; (v) retired teachers; and (vi) authorised functionaries of well-run self-help groups (SHGs) linked to banks; and </li><li> to allow banks to collect reasonable service charges from the customer in a transparent manner under their Board- approved  policy for delivering the services through BC. This should be clearly explained to the customer. </li></ul><p> MicroSave is absolutely convinced that with these and a few additional relaxations of the regulatory regime, India could have close to 100% coverage within a matter of 5-10 years – with a potential un-served market of 400 million, this represents a huge business opportunity. Three challenges remain: </p><ol><li> The requirement that banks involved in delivering e- or m-banking services are currently required to have branches within 30kms (or 15kms in urban areas) of potential customers/agents – which in many areas effectively limits the service provider to a few public sector banks. </li><li> Restrictions on who can act as agents have meant that banks are struggling in their search for large numbers of organised/aggregated agents. In most countries, mobile operator networks&#39; agents or chains of supermarkets, petrol stations or pharmacies are typically used. These chains allow banks to recruit/train and manage agents en masse rather than individually – the latter is a very expensive proposition. </li><li> For remote areas, for example the north east of India, it may be necessary to ask for the current requirement that all transactions be recorded in the books of the bank within 24 hours, to be put into abeyance. </li></ol><p> If these issues were addressed, the opportunities for banks and other financial institutions to leverage technology are extraordinary – there is a domestic remittance market estimated to be “Rs.26,000-40,000 crore” (see <a href="http://bit.ly/2jbYnj">http://bit.ly/2jbYnj</a> ); huge latent demand for a variety of insurance services (if they are appropriately tailored for the low income market); and of course, as has been shown across the globe, the potential for deposit mobilisation given the right products and delivery channels is startling (see for example <a href="http://bit.ly/1rT0x0">http://bit.ly/1rT0×0</a> ). </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/microsave_post_01.jpg class=alignright> <strong>How can interested parties help?</strong> </p><p> As the regulatory environment becomes more conducive for e- and m-banking, we will all need to work together to develop robust, customer-responsive products and channels and to understand the costs and revenues underlying them – thus allowing the development of successful business models that create real value for the poor. Too much of e-/m-banking for the poor remains rhetoric, but the potential is clear – a clearer focus on understanding the needs and behaviour of the poor, and a real commitment by the banks to extending services deep into the rural areas could change not just the endemic financial exclusion, but also much of the development challenges that face the world today. </p><p> _______________________________________________ </p><p> Graham AN Wright helped design and establish the MicroSave programme and is currently Programme Director for India. Graham pioneered much of the core of market-led approach used by MicroSave – in particular the Market Research for MicroFinance tools. He has had a career of two decades of development experience underpinned by five years of experience in management consultancy, training and audit with a leading accounting firm in Europe. He is a reformed Chartered Accountant. </p><p> Graham has provided training and technical assistance to a variety of microfinance institutions in Bangladesh, India, the Philippines and throughout Africa. He helped develop, test and implement a sustainable rural savings and credit programme for BURO, now an influential microfinance institution in Bangladesh. He provided long-term technical assistance to develop a rural finance system, using self-help “Savings and Loan Groups” linked to strong cooperatives in a remote mountainous area of the Philippines. He has also worked on training, systems design, research and evaluation for the usual alphabet soup of donors. </p><p> Graham has authored over 14 training toolkits and 25 papers, including a book entitled “MicroFinance Systems: Designing Quality Financial Services for the Poor” (University Press Ltd, Dhaka and Zed Books, London and New York, 2000). He was also chair of the CGAP Savings Mobilisation Working and a member of the Product Development Groups and is a Research Associate at the Institute of Development Policy and Management, University of Manchester, UK. </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-316> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/mobile-money-and-conflict/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Mobile Money and Conflict">Mobile Money and Conflict</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="View all posts in Blog posts" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on November 18th, 2009  by host – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/mobile-money-and-conflict/#respond" title="Comment on Mobile Money and Conflict">Be the first to comment</a></small> <div class=entry><p>Mobile banking&#39;s potential to leapfrog existing mainstream banking is apparent in countries with large populations without access to traditional banks and financial services. In these cases, mobile banking streamlines existing financial transactions which might take months and cost an exorbitant percentage of the value being exchanged. Instead the instant, low cost money transfer makes these affordable, and even permits transactions which would otherwise be impractical. Another functionality which mobile banking provides, however, that is easy to group together with these streamlined transactions, are transactions which could not have taken place before, not because they were unaffordable or impractical, but because of conflict and forced migration. </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/crisis_post_1.jpg class=alignleft> With significant personal experience among forced migrants from Darfur, Palestine, Iraq, Western Sahara, and Somalia, I have heard firsthand of the economic isolation which cuts ordinary people off from financial transactions which others rely on the world over, even those without access to banks. These conflict zones may lack not only traditional banking infrastructure, but even, at times, access to financial instruments depended upon in the most economically isolated countries. In these situations, when cash may be unavailable or unreliable (because of hyperinflation, or counterfeiting), and other assets not liquid enough to be protected or transported in the face of conflict, the necessity of communication remains paramount, and mobile phone infrastructures continue to be maintained, and to provide a foundational infrastructure for mobile banking. Even in Darfur where the Sudanese government would cut all cell phone service during offensives against rebels, satellite phones could be used in the most isolated areas to transfer credit and maintain lines of communication. Likewise, in Somalia, where widespread violence and anarchy have eroded most confidence in mainstream financial institutions, mobile phone networks are among the better ones in Africa1, and The Economist claims that: “A call from a Somali mobile phone is generally cheaper and clearer than a call from anywhere else in Africa.”2 </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/crisis_post_2.jpg class=alignright> We can see how this potential is actually being exploited a bit more, albeit informally, in Iraq, where “reluctant to risk their lives by visiting a bank, many [Iraqi phone] subscribers transferred money to each other by passing on the serial numbers of scratch cards charged with credit, like gift vouchers.”3  The unique combination of security, liquidity and discreetness allows mobile credit to perform a role which could not be filled by any traditional financial instruments, regardless of time scale or cost. Having recognized the significance to Iraqi communities, “the UN says it has plans to deliver aid to Iraqi refugees in Syria in the same way.”4  This institutional turn to mobile financial transactions underscores the unique place of mobile money in conflict contexts, as no other means is really accessible. One US government intern describes a pilot program for paying Iraqi soldiers with mobile money, because a quarter of them were on leave at any one time because they couldn&#39;t receive their pay.5  If even these large, bureaucratic organizations have found a way to incorporate mobile money into their structures, how much more potential could there be for agile and flexible local NGO&#39;s working on the ground. </p><p>The need for mobile financial transactions in countries from Iraq to Mauritania is not limited to situations of crisis, conflict and forced migration. However the ingenuity and resilience of some of the populations in these countries in the face of these challenges is teaching us how mobile money can solve financial problems that previously could not be addressed at all. In working with FrontlineSMS:Credit as the regional coordinator for the Middle East and North Africa region, I am eager to learn more about the different ways that mobile phone users in these regions are leveraging technology to make a difference in times of conflict and peace. </p><p><img class=alignleft src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_joel.jpg /><br /> <em>This post was contributed by Joel Mitchell, North Africa &amp; Middle East Regional Coordinator for FrontlineSMS:Credit.</em> </p><p> To contact Joel, email <a href=mailto:joel@credit.frontlinesms.com>joel@credit.frontlinesms.com</a> or follow him on Twitter at <a href="http://twitter.com/jdmitchjoel"target=_blank>@jdmitchjoel</a> . </p><h5> ____________________ <br /> <span  > 1。</span> Ford, Nowrasteh, Powell; 2006. “Somalia After State Collapse: Chaos or Improvement?” Independent Institute Working Paper Number 64. November 30, 2006. Oakland, CA. http://www.independent.org. <br /> <span  > 2。</span> Economist Editors. “Mobile Phones” The Economist. December 20-24, 2005. <br /> <span  > 3。</span> Economist Editors. “Iraq&#39;s Mobile Phone Revolution: Better than Freedom?” The Economist. November 14-20, 2009. <br /> <span  > 4。</span> Op. Cit. <br /> 5. <a href="http://a517dogg.blogspot.com/2007/07/mobile-banking-and-poverty-part-1.html"target=_blank>http://a517dogg.blogspot.com/2007/07/mobile-banking-and-poverty-part-1.html</a> </h5></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-281> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/our-own-line-in-the-sand/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Our own line in the sand">Our own line in the sand</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="View all posts in Blog posts" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on November 8th, 2009  by Ben Lyon – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/11/our-own-line-in-the-sand/#comments" title="Comment on Our own line in the sand">1 Comment</a></small> <div class=entry><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/line_in_the_sand.jpg align=left class=alignleft> In response to a lively debate on “the cloud” and “appropriate technology”, Ken Banks of <a href="http://www.kiwanja.net/"trget=_blank>kiwanja.net</a> recently wrote a blog post titled “Our &#39;social mobile&#39; line in the sand”. The purpose of the post was to articulate where FrontlineSMS stands with regard to five key mobile tools for development. In the spirit of openness and precision, we felt it necessary to write a similar post to outline where FrontlineSMS and FrontlineSMS:Credit are both similar and different. </p><p> First, to echo Ken, our primary goal is to provide the end user with a tool that is appropriate and intuitive. Although the levels of sophistication in the mobile space vary, especially when it comes to mobile payments and finance, our aim is to construct a tool that utilizes as many pre-existing channels and competencies as possible. Why reinvent the wheel? </p><p> <span  > <strong>1。</strong></span> <strong>Who is your target audience?</strong> </p><p> Our ideal target audience is Tier 3 and Tier 4 microfinance institutions (MFIs) whose clients have access to some form of mobile payment system. FrontlineSMS:Credit may also benefit institutions that need to send mobile payments en masse. Payroll, compensation, crisis relief, and incentive-based programs are good examples of the latter. </p><p> In the long run, we plan to provide a comparable tool to Tier 1 and Tier 2 MFIs. Doing so, however, will require a more sophisticated, web-based approach and is therefore not a current priority. Further, Tier 3 and Tier 4 MFIs, which typically spring from and align themselves with grassroots needs, are likely to have greater access to rural populations that are un- or under-served in the status quo. </p><p> <span  > <strong>2。</strong></span> <strong>What is your position on scaling?</strong> </p><p> We support scaling and centralization as long as it&#39;s user-driven and practical. Nevertheless, we are hesitant to promote centralized approaches where regulatory and infrastructural ecosystems are weak or ill-defined. To put it simply, it would be imprudent to subject the finances of the unbanked poor to a single point of failure. </p><p> With horizontal scaling, which we prefer, risk is evenly spread across implementing institutions. Any failure is therefore isolated to a particular hub instead of the system as a whole. </p><p> <span  > <strong>3。</strong></span> <strong>How does it replicate and grow?</strong> </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/line_in_the_sand_2.jpg class=alignright> Like FrontlineSMS and FrontlineSMS:Medic, we are driven by “pull” from interested organizations. 100% of our upcoming pilot and beta partners, for instance, initiated contact to collaborate. As a result of time saved from not seeking partners, we can commit the majority of our efforts to getting feedback from potential users and adjusting our designs accordingly. The FrontlineSMS:Credit team is large and geographically scattered for precisely this reason. </p><p> <span  > <strong>4。</strong></span> <strong>What is your position on open sourcing?</strong> </p><p> We consider open sourcing essential for improvement and continued innovation. Unlike FrontlineSMS, however, we will need to closely monitor and scrutinize changes to the source code in order to protect end users from fraud (eg a developer could build a back door into the system to access financial data and PIN numbers). Since economic shocks at the bottom of the pyramid can be a matter of life or death, we will have to ensure that any modifications to the code are both secure and made in good faith. </p><p> <span  > <strong>5。</strong></span> <strong>Does access to the Internet matter?</strong> </p><p> No.  By providing the data bridge necessary to take full advantage of mobile payment systems, MFIs will be able to provide a range of financial services via the cellular network. Although an internet connection will allow MFIs to backup user data (which could also be achieved with a simple thumb drive), one won&#39;t be necessary for FrontlineSMS:Credit to function. </p><p> <strong>Note:</strong> <em>FrontlineSMS:Credit is currently under development and will be available for free download this Spring. It is being designed to function as middleware that will enable any mobile payment system and any management information system (MIS) to communicate in real time. As a result, implementing MFIs will be able to distribute loans, receive repayments and generate robust auditing trails and client credit histories directly from their MIS.</em> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-222> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/arc-finance-highlights-our-raison-detre/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Arc Finance Highlights our Raison D&#8217;être">Arc Finance Highlights our Raison D&#39;être</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="View all posts in Blog posts" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on October 27th, 2009  by host – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/arc-finance-highlights-our-raison-detre/#comments" title="Comment on Arc Finance Highlights our Raison D&#8217;être">4 Comments</a></small> <div class=entry><p> <a href="http://www.arcfinance.org/"target=_blank><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/arc_logo.jpg alt=arc_logo title="arc_logo" width=108 height=106 class="alignleft size-full wp-image-225" border=0 /></a> <em>The nonprofit, Arc Finance, is looking into ways to expand access to financing for modern energy, clean water, and other basic needs globally, and is interested to see how mobile payment systems are being used currently to make payments/remittances possible in rural settings. In the email below, Mike MacHarg of Arc Finance highlights some of the issues facing one NGO making mobile payments to farmers in Kenya.</em> </p><p> Dear XXXX, </p><p> Got some interesting feedback from the group XXXX, that uses Safaricom&#39;s MPesa system to pay its tree farmers (they pay farmers quarterly in Kenya, India and Tanzania for tree planting – through funds raised on the voluntary carbon market). </p><p> <strong>How it works:</strong> </p><p> XXXX has small groups of 8-12 farmers each. XXXX makes quarterly payments to the small group, to a single Safaricom (in Kenya) SIM card held by the group. There is a checks and balance system built in, as at least three farmers from the small group have to show up at the meeting when the transfer is made, and one has the SIM card, another the PIN number for MPesa collection, and a third has the voucher for the payment (voucher is issued beforehand when it is confirmed the trees were actually planted?). </p><p> <strong>Issues and challenges:</strong> </p><p><a href="http://www.safaricom.co.ke/index.php?id=745"target=_blank><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/safaricom.jpg alt=safaricom title="Safaricom公司" width=250 height=230 class="alignright size-full wp-image-229" border=0 /></a> 1) Transaction fees are high relative to the small payments to the farmers. One issue has been that the transfer fees within Safaricom/MPesa are high relative to the small payments being made to the group. Either XXXX has to absorb that cost, or pass it onto the farmers. In Safaricom&#39;s case, it does not pay to make very small payments. </p><p> 2) SIM card deactivation over time: In the small group model, the SIM card is only used quarterly by the group for the money transfer, and for no other purpose. Unfortunately, Safaricom deactivates SIM cards that are dormant for long periods (like 3mo) – so XXXX has faced the issue of having to reactivate all of their small group SIM cards prior to each money transfer. Causes major delay in transfer, and can cause farmer payment meetings to take up to 6 hours. </p><p> Deactivation may be different with different vendors (MTN, Orange), but something to consider. XXXX is trying to determine other ways to keep cards active, such as sending a negligible amount of airtime, say 1 Ksh (there is no fee for transferring air time) – so that the SIMs stay active. </p><p> 3) SIM card registration: this may play into the regulatory environments for mobile payment systems, but XXXX has recently found out that it is “illegal” to register the SIM cards to small groups – and not to an actual business or individual. This probably has to do with “know your customer” regulations that have to do with banking – that are being carried over to mobile money transfer operations. Another thing to consider if you use the small group model. </p><p><img src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/mpesa_news_main.jpg alt=mpesa_news_main title="mpesa_news_main" width=285 height=189 class="alignleft size-full wp-image-234" /> 4) Transfer time: XXXX brings its small groups together on a certain day, and meets with them physically to do the mobile money transfer. While you might think it would be easier to just pay out cash in this setting – there is enough of a security issue that the mobile payments still make more sense. But transfers are not often instantaneous – and intermittent cell phone connections in rural areas can drag out the transfer process for up to 3-4 hours, as each transfer has to be uploaded to MPesa, and then farmers will wait to verify the payment has indeed made it back to their SIM card. </p><p> 5) SIM credit limits: XXXX has to use up to 4 of their own SIM cards to make the payments from, since there are limits (with Safaricom) as to how much credit any individual SIM card can hold at one time. So to make $400 in payments, XXXX might use four SIM cards that have a limit of $100 each. </p><p> 6) Record keeping: To date, Safaricom has been resistant to providing XXXX with records of their individual transfers to each of the small group&#39;s SIM cards. Obviously valuable data for XXXX to have to keep track of payments to farmers, and for now they are reliant on paper based records to keep track of data that Safaricom is already keeping. Safaricom has said that they are looking into making such data available, but has resisted in helping XXXX to date (as it sees no great profit incentive to supply such data). </p><p> <em>Individual and organization names have been redacted for privacy purposes. The email author, Mike MacHarg, is available for comment and can be reached at <br /> <a href=mailto:mike.macharg@gmail.com>mike.macharg “AT” gmail.com</a> .</em> </p></div></div><div class=post><h3 id=post-208> <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/leveraging-technology-for-microfinance/" rel=bookmark title="Permanent Link to Leveraging Technology for Microfinance">Leveraging Technology for Microfinance</a> </h3> <small>Posted in <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/" title="View all posts in Blog posts" rel="category tag">Blog posts</a> on October 19th, 2009  by host – <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/2009/10/leveraging-technology-for-microfinance/#respond" title="Comment on Leveraging Technology for Microfinance">Be the first to comment</a></small> <div class=entry><p> The microfinance sector has arrived at a fork in the road. For a long while it has sought to raise awareness and publicity for the plight of the poor and for funding of its operations. </p><p> With the award of the Nobel Peace Prize in 2006 to Prof Muhammad Yunus of the <a href="http://www.grameen-info.org/"target=_blank>Grameen Bank</a> , the sector has been basking in its glow and has been able to attract a lot of attention and funding for the very good work that it does. </p><p> And this glow has decreased considerably in the past year due to the global economic downturn. MFI&#39;s both big and small have been struggling due to lack of funding and dearth of funding sources. The issue of operational inefficiencies, high operating costs at MFI&#39;s big and small has heightened. The MFI&#39;s customers are also hurting from higher energy, fuel, and food costs. That&#39;s the macro picture. </p><p> MFI&#39;s have limited set of choices to make to improve their financial plight / viability: </p><ol><li> To grow and scale their operations – adding new customers more rapidly and retaining existing ones, </li><li> To increase the interest rates and fees that they charge customers – which allows them to generate more revenue and would help improve their financial bottom-line, ie to be more profitable, </li><li> To reduce customer and staffing “churn”, ie to increase retention rates of existing customers, and of their staff, </li><li> To lower their operating costs </li></ol><p> Confronted with these choices, all MFI&#39;s want to grow and scale their operations. However given the limited funding available, social investors and capital markets only target those MFI&#39;s that are profitable and well managed. And even these MFI&#39;s do not get all of the funding that they may want or desire. </p><p> The other option is to increase rates and fees. With the banks also hurting, they are also seeking other sources for customer growth, and are moving downstream to target customers that have been the domain of MFI&#39;s. The competitive landscape has changed in some geographies and/or is changing in others. If MFI&#39;s were to adopt this option they would do so at their own peril. Customers would vote with their feet and run to another MFI or bank that offers lower rates and fees. </p><p> Most MFI&#39;s have very high “churn” rates of their customers, ie they lose customers after being with them for one loan cycle. And coupled with this they lose lot of staff which means they are constantly losing operational and customer knowledge. </p><p> This then brings us to the last option, to lower operating costs. <span  >如何？</span> MFI&#39;s need to focus and work on the low-hanging fruit to try and reduce their costs. First by adopting policies and practices (eg to provide on-going training on policies, products, processes, and customer service) to retain their “good” performing staff, and to improve customer retention (ie to adopt practices that makes the customer not want to go elsewhere – and customers even these ones do not all move because of price). Secondly, to improve,  streamline and automate their operational processes, to ensure that these processes are properly documented and maintained, and to provide on-going training on these processes to their staff. Most MFI&#39;s, big and small, pay little attention to effectively managing their operational practices and processes. </p><p> This is where we, the technology solutions and service providers, can play a critical role to help MFI&#39;s not just lower their operating costs but can also help them to scale their operations and retain customers. </p><p>The bulk of the MFI&#39;s front-end processes are manual, and fraught with errors, ie loan officers (LOs) use pen &amp; paper to collect customer information, and then this “hieroglyphics” is given to a person in the branch to enter into a system or an Excel spreadsheet; LOs again use pen &amp; paper to track and manage customer repayments, etc … There is little or no credit scoring or credit decisioning capability available to the LO. The time it takes from the initial conversation with the customer to being approved for a loan to loan disbursement is too long. There is little or no info captured on micro businesses in the 2 mile, 5 mile, 10 mile radius of a specfic village or market – such info would be useful to predict the viability of the customer&#39;s business when it comes to making a loan approve or decline decision rather than leaving it to the gut or experience of the LO. </p><p> At the end of the day, MFI&#39;s performance comes down to what their PAR (portfolio at risk) is at day 30, 60, 90, etc. Proactive management of loan repayments is a critical element to keeping PAR low. By providing hand-held or mobile solutions to MFI&#39;s to give to their LO&#39;s that can help manage and track “like” businesses in the area, customer repayment history, being able to print receipts, etc can significantly assist to not just improve PAR but also to help streamline and improve their processes. </p><p> We within the technology sector, and especially at FrontlineSMS:Credit, have a wonderful opportunity to play a significant and a meaningful role to help ease some of the cost burdens faced by MFI&#39;s. I am looking forward to learn more about FrontlineSMS:Credit and to work with the team to help shape its roadmap. </p><p><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-184" title="hillmer_reyes" src=http://credit.frontlinesms.com/wp-content/uploads/team_jiten.jpg alt=team_jiten width=128 height=128 /> <em>Jiten Patel is the Director of Product Development for FrontlineSMS:Credit. He has experience working for both for-profits and non-profits and most recently served as Chief Information Officer of <a href="http://www.villagebanking.org/"target=_blank>FINCA International</a> .</em> To contact Jiten, email <a href=mailto:jiten@credit.frontlinesms.com>Jiten@credit.frontlinesms.com</a> or follow him on Twitter at <a href="http://twitter.com/nomadic_cio"target=_blank>@nomadic_cio</a> . </p></div></div><div class=navigation><div class=alignleft> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/zh-CN/blog/category/blog-posts/0/page/2/" >«旧条目</a></span> </div><div class=alignright></div></div></div><div id=sidebar><ul><li id=rssfeeds><table border=0><tr><td> <span  > <a href="http://credit.frontlinesms.com/feed/">订阅</a></span> </td><td></td><td>
